40|$|CeBr 3 {{crystals}} {{have been}} studied to assess their utility as potential <b>gamma</b> <b>ray</b> <b>spectrometers</b> for future ESA planetary missions. Pulse height spectra, scintillation time profiles, X-ray excited emission spectra, and photoluminescence spectra have been recorded {{as a function of}} temperature between 78 and 600 K. In addition, the influence of exposing CeBr 3 to various doses of <b>gamma</b> <b>rays</b> from a strong 60 Co source on its scintillation performance has been investigated. Radiation, Radionuclides and ReactorsApplied Science...|$|R
